decision_conditions:
Condition : 1 - Unless approved otherwise in writing by the local planning authority, the development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved drawings and specifications, as listed within this decision notice above.
To ensure a satisfactory standard of development, and to allow the local planning authority to review any potential changes to the scheme.

Condition : 2 - This development shall be begun within 5 years from the date of this permission or within 2 years of the date of approval of the last of the Reserved Matters to be approved whichever is the later.
To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.

Condition : 3 - The first application for approvals of Reserved Matters shall not be made to the local planning authority later than four years following the date of this planning permission.
To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.

Condition : 5 - No application or applications shall be submitted to the local planning authority for the approval of Reserved Matters in respect of any of the development hereby permitted later than 14 years following the date of this permission.
To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.

Condition : 6 - No development authorised by any Reserved Matters approval shall be begun more than 16 years from the date of this permission or 2 years from the date of the final Reserved Matters approval, whichever is later.
To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.

Condition : 7 - The development shall be carried out within the scope tested in the approved Environmental Impact Assessment, which was carried out for the approved drawings as listed under Condition 1 of this permission, and incorporate the mitigation measures set out in the Environmental Statement dated April 2014 and in the Environmental Statement Addendum, dated September 2014.
To ensure the development is carried out in accordance with the principles of mitigation that have been assessed in the EIA.

Condition : 8 - The applications for the approval of Reserved Matters submitted under condition 4 shall be in accordance with the Design Code, dated September 2014, and the Design Code Addendum, dated 11 November 2014 or as subsequently amended and agreed in writing by the local planning authority.
To control the appearance and architectural form of the development and to ensure a high quality and co-ordinated design for the built form and landscaping, in accordance with policy IS3 of the Core Strategy and policy DMS1 of the Development Management Policies Document.

Condition : 9 - The applications for the approval of Reserved Matters submitted under condition 4 shall be in accordance with the scale, massing, access and circulation limitations and distributions of uses set by the Parameter Plans.
To ensure the development proceeds on the basis of the scheme on which an Environmental Impact Assessment has been undertaken and to allow the Local Planning Authority to review any potential changes to the scheme in accordance with policy DMS1 of the Development Management Policies Document.

Condition : 10 - The development of the Main Market Site shall be carried out in accordance with the phases, or part thereof, as set out in the approved Phasing and Decant Strategy, dated April 2014, or as may be agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
To ensure the re-provision of the market at the earliest opportunity and reduce uncertainty for the businesses within the market and to ensure the development proceeds on the basis on which the Environmental Impact Assessment as be undertaken.

Condition : 11 - The development permitted by this planning permission shall only be carried out in accordance with the approved Flood Risk Assessment (FRA), dated January 2014, and the mitigation measures detailed within Chapter 8 of the FRA. These mitigation measures include all sleeping accommodation within residential uses are to be set above the 1 in 100 year flood level as derived through breach analysis and the basement energy centres shall be fully tanked to prevent any water ingress and ensure the buildings remain operational during times of flood.
To minimise the risk of internal flooding and to ensure the safety of occupants during a flood, to ensure users of the site are aware of how to act during times of flood to minimise risk and to ensure no additional burden on the emergency services, and to prevent the services to the building being cut off during a flood and to reduce the risk of flooding to the proposed development and future occupants, in accordance with DMPD policy DMS5 and to ensure accordance with the Flood and Water Management Act 2010.

Condition : 12 - The development shall be designed and implemented in accordance with the approved Energy Strategy (URS, April 2014) and Sustainability Statement (URS, April 2014) and Addendum Note (URS, September 2014), unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
To ensure the implementation of sustainable design, low carbon, development and renewable energy in accordance with Core Strategy policy IS2 and DMPD policy DMS3.

Condition : 13 - The total gross external floorspace areas of the uses hereby approved shall be limited to the following:
a) Overall gross external floorspace of all the uses, including parking, servicing, plant and storage, shall not exceed 478,207sq.m. GEA (including 84,330sqm of ancillary basements, multi-storey car parking and the football deck extension)
b) Retail and professional and financial services and food and drink uses (Classes A1 to A5) uses shall not exceed 6,120sq.m. GEA.
c) Office (Class B1) use shall not exceed 12,624sq.m. GEA.
d) Leisure (Class D2) use shall not exceed 1,678sq.m. GEA.
e) Community (Class D1) use shall not exceed 1,511sq.m. GEA.
f) Residential (Class C3) use shall not exceed 303,650sq.m GEA if maximum office accommodation on the Northern Site is provided, or 309,385sq.m. GEA if minimum office accommodation on the Northern Site is provided.
g) Wholesale market (sui generis) use shall not exceed 62,559sq.m. GEA.
To restrict the floorspace of the various uses to the levels proposed and assessed, and to ensure a suitable mix of uses within the development.

Condition : 14 - The total gross external floorspace area of each Development Zone hereby approved shall not exceed the following limits:
Northern Site: 215,466sq.m.
Entrance Site: 44,324sq.m.
Thessaly Road Site: 6,933sq.m.
Apex Site: 58,858sq.m.
To restrict the floorspace of the various Development Zones, to accord with the planning application, and to accord with the assessment in the Environmental Impact Assessment.

Condition : 15 - The residential (Class C3) accommodation hereby approved shall not exceed 3,019 units overall, and the following maximum residential floorspaces within each Development Zone shall not be exceeded:
Northern Site: 206,510sq.m GEA if minimum office accommodation is provided, or 200,774s.qm (GEA) if maximum office accommodation is provided.
Entrance Site: 43,728sq.m GEA
Thessaly Road Site: 6,933sq.m GEA
Apex Site: 52,214sq.m GEA
To control the number of residential units, to accord with the planning application, and to accord with the number and mix of units set out in the Environmental Statement submitted with the application, in accordance with Core Strategy policy IS5.

Condition : 16 - The private residential accommodation across the site shall seek to include a mix of sizes in accordance with the following mix, unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority:
Studio units: 5%
1 bedroom units: 22%
2 bedroom units: 47%
3 bedroom units: 23%
4 bedroom units: 4%
To replicate the unit mix of the residential accommodation to that assessed and in general accordance with Core Strategy policy IS5 and DMPD policy DMH3.

Condition : 17 - Within the Surplus Land Sites the gross external area of flexible retail (A1-A5) shall not exceed the below maximum limits:
Northern Site: 1,758sq.m.
Entrance Site: 438sq.m.
Apex Site: 3,924sq.m.
To restrict the floorspace of the various uses to the levels proposed and assessed and to ensure a suitable mix of uses within the development.

Condition : 18 - The details submitted pursuant to Condition 4 for approval of Reserved Matters in relation to the Northern Site Development Zone shall contain a minimum 3,015sq.m. of business (Class B1) floorspace to be provided across the whole of the Northern Site.
To ensure delivery of office provision within the Vauxhall Embassy district of Nine Elms in line with DMPD policy DMTS13.

Condition : 19 - Unless otherwise approved in writing by the local planning authority on an application pursuant to this condition no individual Class A1, A2, A3, A4 or A5 unit within the development shall exceed 300sq.m.
To prevent large out-of-centre commercial units in accordance with Council policy and to limit internal alterations and ensure that larger units are not implemented without prior consideration by the Local Planning Authority in line with policies DMTS1 and DMTS2.

Condition : 20 - With the exception of the Market Site, notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Permitted Development Order 1995, or any replacement Order, no Class A2, A3, A4 or A5 floorspace implemented pursuant to this planning permission shall subsequently be used for Class A1 purposes without prior written consent from the Local Planning Authority.
To ensure an A1 use is not implemented without prior consideration by the Local Planning Authority and to ensure an appropriate mix of uses in line with policy DMTS1 and DMTS2.

Condition : 21 - The B1 or A2 uses hereby approved shall not include use in connection with the hiring, distribution of or trading in motor vehicles, or in connection with driving instruction, unless otherwise agreed in writing.
Appropriate parking and service facilities are not provided for such uses in accordance with Core Strategy policy IS1 and DMPD policy DMT2.

Condition : 22 - No A1, A2, A3, A4 or A5 unit that may be constructed subject to this planning permission shall be subsequently combined with an adjoining unit of the same use class, if the amalgamation would result in a combined unit that exceeds 300sqm without prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.
To prevent amalgamation of small units to create larger out-of-centre units in line with policy DMTS2 and to limit internal alterations and ensure that larger units are not implemented without prior consideration by the Local Planning Authority in line with policy DMTS1.

Condition : 23 - Unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority, the Class A1 to A5, D1 or D2 premises which are implemented pursuant to this planning permission on the Northern Site, Entrance Site and Apex Site shall not be open to customers other than between 0700 and 2300 in respect of any individually defined unit pursuant to this condition. 
To safeguard the amenities of the neighbourhood and local residents, in accordance with DMPD policy DMS1.

Condition : 24 - The window glass of any shopfronts having first been implemented pursuant to details submitted and approved in association with conditions 74 and 75 shall not be mirrored, painted or be otherwise obscured. No shelving, cabinets or other such obstruction shall be placed at any time within 1m of the shop windows. 
Reason: In order to prevent the creation of a dead frontage and to ensure an appropriate the character and appearance of the streetscene, in accordance with policy DMTS8 and DMS1 of the DMPD submission version.

Condition : 25 - The Market Development Zone shall not be operated other than in accordance with the approved Flower and Fruit & Vegetable Market Employee Travel Plan (April 2014) unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 
To encourage the use of alternative means of travel to the private car and encourage greater use of public transport, cycling and walking as an alternative in accordance with policy IS1 of the Core Strategy.

Condition : 26 - The Market Development Zone shall not be operated other than in accordance with the approved 'Waste Management Strategy (Operational) Market' (April 2014) unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
To ensure appropriate provision is made for storage and disposal, and to minimise the environmental impacts from waste arising from the operation of the development in accordance with DMPD policy DMS1.

Condition : 27 - The parking for the Market Site and the Temporary Flower Market shall be implemented in accordance with the approved Car Parking Management Plan, dated April 2014, and the Transport Assessment Addendum, dated September 2014, unless otherwise approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
To ensure appropriate levels of parking are provided and adequate servicing arrangements and vehicle access, in line with council policy DMT2.

Condition : 28 - The covered consolidation areas and van wash structure within the Market Site Development Zone shall be provided in accordance with the details submitted and will need to achieve the noise levels set within the Environmental Statement Addendum (September 2014). 
In the interests of the appearance of the development and in the interests of the amenities of the neighbourhood in accordance with Council policy DMS1.

Condition : 29 - The van wash facility located in the southern corner of the Market Site hereby approved  shall not operate other than between the hours of 0700 and 1700 Monday to Friday and between 0800 and 1200 on Saturdays and at no other time unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.
In the interest of the amenity of neighbouring residential occupiers, in accordance with DMPD policy DMS1.

Condition : 30 - All plant equipment related to the Market Site shall be located within the designated screened plant areas shown in the plans hereby approved. Plant equipment, including ducting and ventilation equipment, located outside the approved designated plant areas will require written approval from the Local Planning Authority.
In the interests of local amenity and visual appearance, and in accordance with Core Strategy policy IS3.

Condition : 31 - The location of any attenuation tanks and basement areas or other sub ground structure that may be required should be designed to ensure that they do not conflict with the need to deliver semi-mature and mature tree specimens in the detailed landscaping of each Phase of the site submitted pursuant to Condition 4.
To ensure adequate space to plant semi-mature and mature trees with suitable space for them to grow and survive in accordance with policy DMO5.

Condition : 32 - If, during development within any Phase, contamination not previously identified is found to be present at the site then no further development (unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority) shall be carried out within that Phase until the developer has submitted, and obtained written approval from the Local Planning Authority for, a remediation strategy detailing how this unsuspected contamination shall be dealt with. The remediation strategy shall be implemented as approved, verified and reported to the satisfaction of the Local Planning Authority.
For the protection of Controlled Waters as a result of unexpected contamination during development groundworks, in accordance with Council policy DMS5 and DMS6.

Condition : 33 - Whilst the principles and installation of sustainable drainage schemes are to be encouraged, no infiltration of surface water drainage into the ground is permitted other than with the express written consent of the Local Planning Authority, which may be given for those parts of the site where it has been demonstrated that there is no resultant unacceptable risk to Controlled Waters. The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approval details.
For the protection of Controlled Waters in accordance with Council policy DMS5 and DMS6.

Condition : 34 - No development shall commence within any Development Zone site until a Site Wide Phasing Plan which describes the phasing of the development across the Development Zones has been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority and will include a separate phase for Building N8. The development shall not be carried out otherwise than in accordance with the approved Site Wide Phasing Plan (including the separate phase for Building N8), unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
In order to ensure a suitable phasing plan is produced that can deliver the development in a table manner and timeframe.

Condition : 36 - No development shall commence within a Development Zone until a detailed surface water drainage scheme for that Development Zone, based on the approved Drainage Strategy (April 2014), has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The drainage strategy should demonstrate that the surface water run-off generated up to and including the critical duration 1 in 100 year storm event will be managed by sustainable drainage systems to achieve at least 50 per cent attenuation of the undeveloped (existing) sites' surface water run off aiming for further improvement to the equivalent of Greenfield run off rates on the Northern and Entrance Sites following the corresponding rainfall event. The scheme shall subsequently be implemented in accordance with the approved details before the development is completed. 
To ensure a sustainable drainage system is implemented to manage the increased risk of flooding, to improve and protect water quality and improve habitat and amenity in accordance with Council policies DMS5, DMS6 and the Mayor's London Plan policy 5.13 and to ensure accordance with the Flood and Water Management Act 2010.

Condition : 37 - Development shall not commence in any Development Zone until a related drainage strategy detailing any on and/or off site drainage works for that Development Zone and accordance with the approved Drainage Strategy (April 2014), has been submitted to and approved by the local planning authority in consultation with the sewage undertaker. No discharge of foul or surface water from the site shall be accepted in the public system until the drainage works referred to in the strategy have been completed. The drainage works to be undertaken in accordance with the approved drainage strategy.
To ensure a sustainable drainage system is implemented and that sufficient capacity is made available to cope with the new development to avoid adverse environmental impacts upon the community.

Condition : 38 - Prior to the commencement of development in each Floorspace Phase, a Flood Management Plan/Emergency Response Plan shall be produced and submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval in writing in accordance with the FRA recommendations. This shall include identification and provision of safe route(s) or safe refuge areas within the buildings for occupants to use during times of flood. The plan shall be implemented as approved, unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
To ensure the safety of occupants during a flood, to ensure users of the site are aware of how to act during times of flood to minimise risk and to ensure no additional burden on the emergency services, in accordance with DMPD policy DMS5 and to ensure accordance with the Flood and Water Management Act 2010.

Condition : 39 - Prior to commencement of development in each phase, the tree protection measures during construction works for the trees to be retained will be implemented in accordance with the measures set out in the Arboricultural Impact Assessment Report of the Environmental Statement, dated April 2014.
To ensure sufficient protection is given to the on-site trees to be retained, in accordance with policy DMO5.

Condition : 40 - Prior to the commencement of development in each phase, the mitigation measures to protect wild mammals during the construction and demolition phase will be implemented in accordance with the measures set out in the Environmental Statement, dated April 2014.
To ensure sufficient protection is given to the on-site ecology, in accordance with policy DMO4.

Condition : 41 - Prior to commencement of development on the Entrance Site, details of an internal investigation on the existing residential Victorian property are to be carried out in line with the Environmental Statement, dated April 2014, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority.
In order to assess the ecological value of the site in accordance with Council policy DMO4.

Condition : 42 - A) No development other than demolition to existing ground level shall take place until the applicant (or their heirs and successors in title) has secured the implementation of a programme of archaeological evaluation site work in accordance with a Written Scheme of Investigation which has been submitted by the applicant and approved by the local planning authority in writing and a report on that evaluation has been submitted to and approved by the local planning authority in writing. 

B) Under Part A, the applicant (or their heirs and successors in title) shall implement a programme of archaeological investigation in accordance with a Written Scheme of Investigation. 

C) Under Part A, the applicant (or their heirs and successors in title) shall implement a programme of archaeological mitigation in accordance with a Written Scheme of Investigation. 

D) The site investigation and post-investigation assessment will be completed prior to one year post the completion date of the development as defined by the borough building regulation officer, in accordance with the programme set out in the Written Scheme of Investigation approved under Part (A), and the provision for analysis, publication via the Battersea Channel Project report and dissemination of the non-Battersea Channel Project archaeological results and archive deposition has been secured.

Condition : 43 - Prior to the commencement of development in any Phase involving below ground works the following components of a scheme to deal with the risks associated with land and groundwater contamination of the site shall each be submitted to and approved, in writing, by the local planning authority:
1) A preliminary risk assessment which has identified:
 all previous uses
 potential contaminants associated with those uses
 a conceptual model of the site indicating sources, pathways and receptors
 potentially unacceptable risks arising from contamination at the site.
2) A site investigation scheme, based on (1) to provide information for a detailed assessment of the risk to all receptors that may be affected, including those off site. The investigation shall comply with the guidance contained in BS 10175:2011 - Investigation of potentially contaminated sites - Code of practice, as amended.
3) The results of the site investigation and detailed risk assessment referred to in (2) and, based on these, an options appraisal and remediation/mitigation  strategy that addresses these risks and giving full details of the remediation measures required and how they are to be undertaken. The approved scheme of remediation/mitigation shall be implemented as part of the redevelopment of the site.
4) A verification plan providing details of the data that will be collected in order to demonstrate that the works set out in the remediation strategy in (3) are complete and identifying any requirements for longer-term monitoring of pollutant linkages, maintenance and arrangements for contingency action.
Any changes to these components require the express consent of the local planning authority. The scheme shall be implemented as approved. Occupation of an identified stage of development shall not be permitted until the measures contained in this condition have been undertaken to the satisfaction of the Council, and of the Environment Agency in respect of controlled waters.
For the p

Condition : 44 - No piling or other foundation designs using penetrative methods shall take place in any Phase containing piling or foundation works until a piling method statement (detailing the type of piling to be undertaken and the methodology by which such piling will be carried out, including measures to prevent and minimise the potential for damage to subsurface water or sewerage infrastructure, and the programme for the works) has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority in consultation with the relevant water or sewerage undertaker. Any piling must be undertaken in accordance with the terms of the approved piling method statement. 
To ensure no adverse impact on local underground water and sewerage utility infrastructure and to ensure there is no unacceptable risks to underlying groundwater through contamination in accordance with Council policy IS4, DMPD policies DMS5 and DMS6 and to ensure accordance with the Flood and Water Management Act 2010 and to ensure there is no conflict with the construction of the Northern Line Extension.

Condition : 45 - Prior to the commencement of each Floorspace Phase (other than demolition and site enabling works), a detailed Cultural Strategy and Action Plan for that Phase, which shows how it will deliver the overarching agreed Cultural Strategy dated April 2014, shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval. The details approved shall be implemented unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.

Condition : 93 - Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL):  From the information available, it appears that the development permitted is subject to a Community Infrastructure Levy charge in accordance with the Community Infrastructure Levy Regulations 2010 (as amended). You or the relevant interested parties are required to provide the Council with the information set out in the Regulations.  The process for the collection of CIL includes:

- the requirement to complete an "Assumption of Liability" form as soon as possible;
- to claim charitable exemption, social housing relief, self-build exemption or residential annex/extension exemption you or the relevant interested party must complete the correct claim form 
The Council will issue a Liability Notice(s) which details the charges due.
As soon as the developer, landowner of other interested party(ies) is aware of the date when development is going to start they must also submit a "Commencement Notice". 
Failure to comply with the Regulations, including failure to complete the forms when required or providing inaccurate information can lead to surcharges, invalidate claims for relief or exemption from the charge, or other penalties as set out in the Regulations.
General information on the Community Infrastructure Levy, including the forms mentioned above can be found on the Planning Portal (www.planningportal.gov.uk).
Details of the Mayoral CIL can be found on the GLA and TfL websites (www.london.gov.uk and www.tfl.gov.uk).

The Assumption of Liability Form, Claiming of Exemption or Relief Forms and Commencement Notice must be sent to:

Community Infrastructure Levy

London

cil@wandsworth.gov.uk
